# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: van-emde-boas-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] A bitwise trie is a special form of trie where each node with its child-branches represents a bit sequence of one or more bits of a key.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] A **bitwise trie with bitmap** uses a bitmap to denote valid child branches.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] A trie is a type of search tree where – unlike for example a B-tree – keys are not stored in the nodes but in the path to leaves.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The key is distributed across the tree structure.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] In a "classic" trie, each node with its child-branches represents one symbol of the alphabet of one position (character) of a key.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] To give an example that explains the difference between "classic" tries and bitwise tries: For numbers as keys, the alphabet for a trie could consist of the symbols '0' ..
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] '9' to represent digits of a number in the decimal system and the nodes would have up to 10 possible children.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] There are multiple straight forward approaches to implement such a trie as physical data structure.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] These approaches get worse for larger alphabets, if, for example, the key is a string of Unicode characters.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Treating the key as bit-sequence allows to have a fixed cardinality per node.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Bagwell presented a time and space efficient solution for tries named Array Mapped Tree (AMT).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The Hash array mapped trie (HAMT) is based on AMT.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The compact trie node representation uses a bitmap to mark every valid branch – a **bitwise trie with bitmap**.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The AMT uses eight 32-bit bitmaps per node to represent a 256-ary trie that is able to represent an 8 bit sequence per node.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] With 64-Bit-CPUs (64-bit computing) a variation is to have a 64-ary trie with only one 64-bit bitmap per node that is able to represent a 6 bit sequence.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] To determine the index of the child pointer of a node for such a given 6-bit value, the amount of preceding child pointers has to be calculated.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] It turns out that this can be implemented quite efficiently.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The offset to find the index based on the current node index is the amount of least significant bits set in the bitmap before the target position plus one for the bitmap.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The amount of least significant bits set can be calculated efficiently with constant time complexity using simple bit operations and a CTPOP (count population) operation that determines the number of set bits, which is available as Long.bitCount() in Java.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] CTPOP itself can be implemented quite efficiently using a "bit-hack" and many modern CPUs even provide CTPOP as a dedicated instruction treated by compilers as intrinsic function.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] In this example implementation for a bitwise trie with bitmap, nodes are placed in an array of long (64-bit) integers.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] A node is identified by the position (index) in that array.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The index of the root node marks the root of the trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Nodes are allocated from unused space in that array, extending the array if necessary.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] In addition, nodes, that are replaced, are collected in free lists and their space is recycled.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Without this recycling, the data structure can be used to implement a persistent data structure by just keeping the previous root index and never overriding existing nodes but always creating a copy of a changed node.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Leaf nodes are inlined: Instead of having a child-pointer to a leaf node, the bitmap of the leaf node itself is stored.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The get method tests, if a key is part of the set.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The key is delivered as byte[] where each byte represents one 6-bit bit sequence of the key – so only 6 of the 8 bits per byte are used.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Set operators for intersection (and), union (or) and difference (minus) are feasible using a flyweight pattern as shown below.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] An interface represents physical nodes and "virtual" result nodes of an operator.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Instances of this interface are created on demand during a trie traversal.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Compound expressions, involving more than one operator, can be expressed directly by combining these operators as an operator can be used as argument (input) for another operator.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The intersection operator is very efficient as it automatically performs pruning even over subexpressions.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Nonrelevant child nodes don't have to be accessed because the bitmap and a bitwise AND operation allows to determine the result upfront.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] Using the virtual node approach, range queries can be accomplished by intersecting a range generating virtual trie (see below) with another operator.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/bitwise-trie-with-bitmap] The example shows the usage with 32-bit integers as keys.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] In computer science, a **fusion tree** is a type of tree data structure that implements an associative array on w-bit integers on a finite universe, where each of the input integers has size less than 2w and is non-negative.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] When operating on a collection of n key–value pairs, it uses *O*(*n*) space and performs searches in *O*(log*w* *n*) time, which is asymptotically faster than a traditional self-balancing binary search tree, and also better than the van Emde Boas tree for large values of w.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] It achieves this speed by using certain constant-time operations that can be done on a machine word.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Fusion trees were invented in 1990 by Michael Fredman and Dan Willard.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Several advances have been made since Fredman and Willard's original 1990 paper.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] A dynamic version of fusion trees using hash tables was proposed in 1996 which matched the original structure's *O*(log*w* *n*) runtime in expectation.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Another dynamic version using exponential tree was proposed in 2007 which yields worst-case runtimes of *O*(log*w* *n* + log log *n*) per operation.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Finally, it was shown that dynamic fusion trees can perform each operation in *O*(log*w* *n*) time deterministically.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] This data structure implements add key, remove key, search key, and predecessor (next smaller value) and successor (next larger value) search operations for a given key.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] The partial result of most significant bit locator in constant time has also helped further research.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Fusion trees utilize word-level parallelism to be efficient, performing computation on several small integers, stored in a single machine word, simultaneously to reduce the number of total operations.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] A fusion tree is essentially a B-tree with branching factor of *w*1/5 (any small exponent is also possible as it will not have a great impact on the height of the tree), which gives it a height of *O*(log*w* *n*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] To achieve the desired runtimes for updates and queries, the fusion tree must be able to search a node containing up to *w*1/5 keys in constant time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] This is done by compressing ("sketching") the keys so that all can fit into one machine word, which in turn allows comparisons to be done in parallel.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] So, a series of computations involving sketching, parallel comparison and most significant bit index locator, help reach the required solution.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Sketching is the method by which each w-bit key at a node containing k keys is compressed into only *k* − 1 bits.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Each key x may be thought of as a path in the full binary tree of height w starting at the root and ending at the leaf corresponding to x.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] This path can be processed by recursively searching the left child of *i* if the *ith* bit is 0, and the right child if it is 1, generally, until all bits are scanned.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] To distinguish two paths, it suffices to look at their branching point (the first bit where any two keys differ).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] As there are a maximum of *k* keys, there will not be more than *k-1* branching points, which means that no more than *k-1* bits are required to identify a key.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] And hence, no sketch will have more than *k-1* bits.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] An important property of the sketch function is that it preserves the order of the keys.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] That is, sketch(*x*) < sketch(*y*) for any two keys *x* < *y*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] So, for the entire range of keys, sketch(x0)<sketch(x1)<...<sketch(xk-1) because if the binary-tree-like path is followed, the nodes will be ordered in such a manner that x0<x1<...<xk-1.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] With only standard word operations, such as those of the C programming language, it is difficult to directly compute the perfect sketch of a key in constant time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Instead, the sketch bits can be packed into a range of size at most *r*4, using bitwise AND and multiplication, called the approximate sketch, which does have all the important bits but also some additional useless bits spread out in a predictable pattern.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] The bitwise AND operation serves as a mask to remove all these non-sketch bits from the key, while the multiplication shifts the sketch bits into a small range.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Like the "perfect" sketch, the approximate sketch also preserves the order of the keys and means that sketch(x0)<sketch(x1)<...<sketch(xk-1).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Some preprocessing is needed to determine the correct multiplication constant.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Each sketch bit in location *b**i* will get shifted to *b**i* + *m**i* via a multiplication by *m* = $\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{r}$ 2*m**i*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] *b**i* + *m**i* is a strictly increasing function of *i*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] That is, the order of the sketch bits is preserved even in x'.m.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] That is, the sketch bits are packed into a range of size at most *r*4, where r ≤ O(w1/5).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] An inductive argument shows how the *m**i* can be constructed.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Then pick the smallest integer *m**t* such that both properties (1) and (2) are satisfied.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Thus, there are less than *tr*2 ≤ *r*3 values that *m**t* must avoid.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Multiply the key by the predetermined constant *m* as calculated above.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] This operation actually requires two machine words, but this can still be done in constant time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Mask out all but the shifted sketch bits.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] These are now contained in a contiguous block of at most *r*4 < *w*4/5 bits.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] The purpose of the compression achieved by sketching is to allow all of the keys to be stored in one *w*-bit word.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Here, all sketch words are clubbed together in one string by prepending a set bit to each of them.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] We can assume that the sketch function uses exactly *b* ≤ *r*4 bits.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Then each block uses 1 + *b* ≤ *w*4/5 bits, and since *k* ≤ *w*1/5, the total number of bits in the node sketch is at most *w*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] A brief notational aside: for a bit string *s* and nonnegative integer *m*, let *s**m* denote the concatenation of *s* to itself *m* times.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] If *t* is also a bit string, *st* denotes the concatenation of *t* to *s*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] The node sketch makes it possible to search the keys for any *b*-bit integer *y*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Let *z* = (0*y*)*k*, which can be computed in constant time (multiply *y* by the constant (0*b*1)*k*), to make it as long as the node sketch such that each word in the node sketch can be compared with the query integer *y* in one operation, demonstrating word-level parallelism.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] If *y* were 5 bits long, it would be multiplied by 000001....000001 to get sketch(y)k.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] The difference between sketch(xi) and 0y results in the leading bit for each block to be 1, if and only if sketch(y) $\leq$ sketch(xi).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Take the bitwise AND of the difference and the constant (10*b*)*k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] This clears all but the leading bit of each block.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Find the most significant bit of the result, to identify the exact index of transition from elements with sketch smaller than the query sketch to those greater than the query sketch.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Compute *i,* the rank of the sketch, using the fact that the leading bit of the *i*-th block has index *i*(*b*+1).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Unfortunately, this does give the exact predecessor or successor of *q*, because the location of the sketch of *q* among the sketches of all the values may not be the same as the location of *q* in all the actual values.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] What is true is that, among all of the keys, either *x**i*-1 or *x**i* has the longest common prefix with *q*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] This is because any key *y* with a longer common prefix with *q* would also have more sketch bits in common with *q*, and thus `sketch`(*y*) would be closer to `sketch`(*q*) than any `sketch`(*x**j*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] The length longest common prefix between two *w*-bit integers *a* and *b* can be computed in constant time by finding the most significant bit of the bitwise XOR between *a* and *b*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] This can then be used to mask out all but the longest common prefix.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Note that *p* identifies exactly where *q* branches off from the set of keys.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] If the next bit of *q* is 0, then the successor of *q* is contained in the *p*1 subtree, and if the next bit of *q* is 1, then the predecessor of *q* is contained in the *p*0 subtree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Compute the longest common prefix *p* of *q* and either *x**i*-1 or *x**i* (taking the longer of the two).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Let *l*-1 be the length of the longest common prefix *p*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Use parallel comparison to search for the predecessor of `sketch`(*e*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Once either the predecessor or successor of *q* is found, the exact position of *q* among the set of keys is determined.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] An application of fusion trees to hash tables was given by Willard, who describes a data structure for hashing in which an outer-level hash table with hash chaining is combined with a fusion tree representing each hash chain.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] In hash chaining, in a hash table with a constant load factor, the average size of a chain is constant, but additionally with high probability all chains have size *O*(log *n* / log log *n*), where n is the number of hashed items.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] This chain size is small enough that a fusion tree can handle searches and updates within it in constant time per operation.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] Therefore, the time for all operations in the data structure is constant with high probability.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] More precisely, with this data structure, for every inverse-quasipolynomial probability *p*(*n*) = exp((log *n*)*O*(1)), there is a constant C such that the probability that there exists an operation that exceeds time C is at most *p*(*n*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] The computational model for the Fusion Tree algorithm is a Word RAM with a specific instruction set, including arithmetic instructions - addition, subtraction and multiplication (all performed modulo 2*w*) and Boolean operations - bitwise AND, NOT etc.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] A double-precision multiplication instruction is also included.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/fusion-tree] It has been shown that removal of the latter instruction makes it impossible to sort faster than *O*(*n* log *n*), unless it is permitted to use memory space of nearly 2*w* words (in contrast to linear space used by Fusion Trees), or include other instructions instead.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In computer science, a **priority queue** is an abstract data type similar to a regular queue where each element has an associated priority determining its order of service.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Priority queue serves highest priority items first.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Priority values have to be instances of an ordered data type, and higher priority can be given either to the lesser or to the greater values with respect to the given order relation.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For example, in the Java standard library, the PriorityQueue class considers the lowest element with respect to their order as having the highest priority.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] While priority queues are often implemented using heaps, they are conceptually distinct.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] A priority queue can be implemented with a heap or with other methods; just as a list can be implemented with a linked list or with an array.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Stacks and queues can be implemented as particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In a stack, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically increasing; thus, the last element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In a queue, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically decreasing; thus, the first element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In some implementations, if two elements have the same priority, they are served in the same order in which they were enqueued.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In other implementations, the order of elements with the same priority is undefined.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] One can create a simple, but inefficient priority queue in a number of ways.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] These naive implementations can demonstrate the expected behaviour of a priority queue in a simpler manner.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] To improve performance, priority queues are typically based on a heap, giving $O(\log n)$ performance for inserts and removals, and $O(n)$ to build the heap initially from a set of n elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Variants of the basic heap data structure such as pairing heaps or Fibonacci heaps can provide better bounds for some operations.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] From a space-complexity standpoint, using self-balancing binary search tree with linked list takes more storage, since it requires storing extra references to other nodes.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] From a computational-complexity standpoint, priority queues are congruent to sorting algorithms.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The section on the equivalence of priority queues and sorting algorithms, below, describes how efficient sorting algorithms can create efficient priority queues.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] There are several specialized heap data structures that either supply additional operations or outperform heap-based implementations for specific types of keys, specifically integer keys.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For applications that do many "peek" operations for every "`extract-min`" operation, the time complexity for peek actions can be reduced to $O(1)$ in all tree and heap implementations by caching the highest priority element after every insertion and removal.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For insertion, this adds at most a constant cost, since the newly inserted element is compared only to the previously cached minimum element.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For deletion, this at most adds an additional "peek" cost, which is typically cheaper than the deletion cost, so overall time complexity is not significantly impacted.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Monotone priority queues are specialized queues that are optimized for the case where no item is ever inserted that has a lower priority (in the case of min-heap) than any item previously extracted.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This restriction is met by several practical applications of priority queues.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The semantics of priority queues naturally suggest a sorting method: insert all the elements to be sorted into a priority queue, and sequentially remove them; they will come out in sorted order.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This is actually the procedure used by several sorting algorithms, once the layer of abstraction provided by the priority queue is removed.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] A sorting algorithm can also be used to implement a priority queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For example, if one has an $O(n\log n)$ sort algorithm, one can create a priority queue with $O(1)$ pulling and $O(\log n)$ insertion.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] A priority queue is often considered to be a "container data structure".
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The Standard Template Library (STL), and the C++ 1998 standard, specifies std::priority_queue as one of the STL container adaptor class templates.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] However, it does not specify how two elements with same priority should be served, and indeed, common implementations will not return them according to their order in the queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Unlike actual STL containers, it does not allow iteration of its elements (it strictly adheres to its abstract data type definition).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] STL also has utility functions for manipulating another random-access container as a binary max-heap.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The Boost libraries also have an implementation in the library heap.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Python's heapq module implements a binary min-heap on top of a list.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Java's library contains a `PriorityQueue` (`java.util.PriorityQueue`) class, which implements a min-priority-queue as a binary heap.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] .NET's library contains a System.Collections.Generic.PriorityQueue class, which implements an array-backed, quaternary min-heap.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Scala's library contains a scala.collection.mutable.PriorityQueue class, which implements a max-priority-queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Go's library contains a container/heap module, which implements a min-heap on top of any compatible data structure.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Rust's standard library contains a std::collections::BinaryHeap struct, which implements a priority queue with a binary heap.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The Standard PHP Library extension contains the class SplPriorityQueue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Apple's Core Foundation framework contains a CFBinaryHeap structure, which implements a min-heap.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Priority queuing can be used to manage limited resources such as bandwidth on a transmission line from a network router.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In the event of outgoing traffic queuing due to insufficient bandwidth, all other queues can be halted to send the traffic from the highest priority queue upon arrival.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This ensures that the prioritized traffic (such as real-time traffic, e.g. an RTP stream of a VoIP connection) is forwarded with the least delay and the least likelihood of being rejected due to a queue reaching its maximum capacity.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] All other traffic can be handled when the highest priority queue is empty.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Another approach used is to send disproportionately more traffic from higher priority queues.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Many modern protocols for local area networks also include the concept of priority queues at the media access control (MAC) sub-layer to ensure that high-priority applications (such as VoIP or IPTV) experience lower latency than other applications which can be served with best-effort service.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Examples include IEEE 802.11e (an amendment to IEEE 802.11 which provides quality of service) and ITU-T G.hn (a standard for high-speed local area network using existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Usually a limitation (policer) is set to limit the bandwidth that traffic from the highest priority queue can take, in order to prevent high priority packets from choking off all other traffic.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This limit is usually never reached due to high level control instances such as the Cisco Callmanager, which can be programmed to inhibit calls which would exceed the programmed bandwidth limit.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Another use of a priority queue is to manage the events in a discrete event simulation.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The events are added to the queue with their simulation time used as the priority.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The execution of the simulation proceeds by repeatedly pulling the top of the queue and executing the event thereon.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] When the graph is stored in the form of adjacency list or matrix, priority queue can be used to extract minimum efficiently when implementing Dijkstra's algorithm, although one also needs the ability to alter the priority of a particular vertex in the priority queue efficiently.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] If instead, a graph is stored as node objects, and priority-node pairs are inserted into a heap, altering the priority of a particular vertex is not necessary if one tracks visited nodes.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Once a node is visited, if it comes up in the heap again (having had a lower priority number associated with it earlier), it is popped-off and ignored.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Huffman coding requires one to repeatedly obtain the two lowest-frequency trees.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] A priority queue is one method of doing this.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Best-first search algorithms, like the A* search algorithm, find the shortest path between two vertices or nodes of a weighted graph, trying out the most promising routes first.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] A priority queue (also known as the *fringe*) is used to keep track of unexplored routes; the one for which the estimate (a lower bound in the case of A*) of the total path length is smallest is given highest priority.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] If memory limitations make best-first search impractical, variants like the SMA* algorithm can be used instead, with a double-ended priority queue to allow removal of low-priority items.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The Real-time Optimally Adapting Meshes (ROAM) algorithm computes a dynamically changing triangulation of a terrain.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] It works by splitting triangles where more detail is needed and merging them where less detail is needed.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The algorithm assigns each triangle in the terrain a priority, usually related to the error decrease if that triangle would be split.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The algorithm uses two priority queues, one for triangles that can be split and another for triangles that can be merged.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In each step the triangle from the split queue with the highest priority is split, or the triangle from the merge queue with the lowest priority is merged with its neighbours.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Using min heap priority queue in Prim's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a connected and undirected graph, one can achieve a good running time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This min heap priority queue uses the min heap data structure which supports operations such as `insert`, `minimum`, `extract-min`, `decrease-key`.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In this implementation, the weight of the edges is used to decide the priority of the vertices.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Lower the weight, higher the priority and higher the weight, lower the priority.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Parallelization can be used to speed up priority queues, but requires some changes to the priority queue interface.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The reason for such changes is that a sequential update usually only has ${\textstyle O(1)}$ or ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost, and there is no practical gain to parallelize such an operation.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] One possible change is to allow the concurrent access of multiple processors to the same priority queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The second possible change is to allow batch operations that work on ${\textstyle k}$ elements, instead of just one element.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For example, `extractMin` will remove the first ${\textstyle k}$ elements with the highest priority.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] If the priority queue allows concurrent access, multiple processes can perform operations concurrently on that priority queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] First of all, the definition of the semantics of the individual operations is no longer obvious.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For example, if two processes want to extract the element with the highest priority, should they get the same element or different ones?
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This restricts parallelism on the level of the program using the priority queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In addition, because multiple processes have access to the same element, this leads to contention.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The concurrent access to a priority queue can be implemented on a Concurrent Read, Concurrent Write (CRCW) PRAM model.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In the following the priority queue is implemented as a skip list.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In addition, an atomic synchronization primitive, CAS, is used to make the skip list lock-free.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The nodes of the skip list consists of a unique key, a priority, an array of pointers, for each level, to the next nodes and a `delete` mark.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The `delete` mark marks if the node is about to be deleted by a process.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This ensures that other processes can react to the deletion appropriately.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] If the concurrent access to a priority queue is allowed, conflicts may arise between two processes.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For example, a conflict arises if one process is trying to insert a new node, but at the same time another process is about to delete the predecessor of that node.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] There is a risk that the new node is added to the skip list, yet it is not longer reachable.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In this setting, operations on a priority queue is generalized to a batch of ${\textstyle k}$ elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For instance, `k_extract-min` deletes the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the priority queue and returns those.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In a shared-memory setting, the parallel priority queue can be easily implemented using parallel binary search trees and join-based tree algorithms.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] In particular, `k_extract-min` corresponds to a *split* on the binary search tree that has ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost and yields a tree that contains the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] `k_insert` can be applied by a *union* of the original priority queue and the batch of insertions.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] If the batch is already sorted by the key, `k_insert` has ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}}))}$ cost.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Otherwise, we need to first sort the batch, so the cost will be ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}})+k\log k)=O(k\log n)}$ .
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Other operations for priority queue can be applied similarly.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] For instance, `k_decrease-key` can be done by first applying `difference` and then `union`, which first deletes the elements and then inserts them back with the updated keys.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] All these operations are highly parallel, and the theoretical and practical efficiency can be found in related research papers.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The rest of this section discusses a queue-based algorithm on distributed memory.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] We assume each processor has its own local memory and a local (sequential) priority queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The elements of the global (parallel) priority queue are distributed across all processors.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] A `k_insert` operation assigns the elements uniformly random to the processors which insert the elements into their local queues.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Note that single elements can still be inserted into the queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Using this strategy the global smallest elements are in the union of the local smallest elements of every processor with high probability.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Thus each processor holds a representative part of the global priority queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This property is used when `k_extract-min` is executed, as the smallest ${\textstyle m}$ elements of each local queue are removed and collected in a result set.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The elements in the result set are still associated with their original processor.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The number of elements ${\textstyle m}$ that is removed from each local queue depends on ${\textstyle k}$ and the number of processors ${\textstyle p}$ .
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] By parallel selection the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the result set are determined.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] With high probability these are the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] If not, ${\textstyle m}$ elements are again removed from each local queue and put into the result set.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This is done until the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements are in the result set.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Now these ${\textstyle k}$ elements can be returned.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] All other elements of the result set are inserted back into their local queues.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The running time of `k_extract-min` is expected ${\textstyle O({\frac {k}{p}}\log(n))}$ , where ${\textstyle k=\Omega (p\cdot \log(p))}$ and ${\textstyle n}$ is the size of the priority queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The priority queue can be further improved by not moving the remaining elements of the result set directly back into the local queues after a `k_extract-min` operation.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] This saves moving elements back and forth all the time between the result set and the local queues.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] By removing several elements at once a considerable speedup can be reached.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] But not all algorithms can use this kind of priority queue.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] Dijkstra's algorithm for example can not work on several nodes at once.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] The algorithm takes the node with the smallest distance from the priority queue and calculates new distances for all its neighbor nodes.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] If you would take out ${\textstyle k}$ nodes, working at one node could change the distance of another one of the ${\textstyle k}$ nodes.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/priority-queue] So using k-element operations destroys the label setting property of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] A **van Emde Boas tree** (Dutch pronunciation: [vɑn ˈɛmdə ˈboːɑs]), also known as a **vEB tree** or **van Emde Boas priority queue**, is a tree data structure which implements an associative array with *m*-bit integer keys.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] It was invented by a team led by Dutch computer scientist Peter van Emde Boas in 1975.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] It performs all operations in *O*(log *m*) time (assuming that an m bit operation can be performed in constant time), or equivalently in $O(\log \log M)$ time, where $M=2^{m}$ is the largest element that can be stored in the tree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The parameter M is not to be confused with the actual number of elements stored in the tree, by which the performance of other tree data-structures is often measured.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The standard vEB tree has an unideal space efficiency of $O(M)$ .
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] For example, for storing 32-bit integers (i.e., when $m=32$ ), it requires $M=2^{32}$ bits of storage.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] To resolve this, vEB trees can be modified to achieve $O(n\log M)$ space, or similar data structures with equivalent asymptotic time efficiency and space efficiency of $O(n)$ (where n is the number of stored elements) can be used.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] A vEB tree also supports the operations *Minimum* and *Maximum*, which return the minimum and maximum element stored in the tree respectively.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] These both run in $O(1)$ time, since the minimum and maximum element are stored as attributes in each tree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] A vEB tree T over the universe $\{0,\ldots ,M-1\}$ has a root node that stores an array T.children of length ${\sqrt {M}}$ .
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] T.children[i] is a pointer to a vEB tree that is responsible for the values $\{i{\sqrt {M}},\ldots ,(i+1){\sqrt {M}}-1\}$ .
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Additionally, *T* stores two values T.min and T.max as well as an auxiliary vEB tree T.aux.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Data is stored in a vEB tree as follows: The smallest value currently in the tree is stored in T.min and largest value is stored in T.max.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Note that T.min is not stored anywhere else in the vEB tree, while T.max is.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] If *T* is empty then we use the convention that T.max=−1 and T.min=M.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Any other value x is stored in the subtree T.children[i] where $i=\lfloor x/{\sqrt {M}}\rfloor$ .
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The auxiliary tree T.aux keeps track of which children are non-empty, so T.aux contains the value j if and only if T.children[j] is non-empty.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The operation FindNext(T, x) that searches for the successor of an element *x* in a vEB tree proceeds as follows: If *x*<T.min then the search is complete, and the answer is T.min.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] If x≥T.max then the next element does not exist, return M.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, let $i=\lfloor x/{\sqrt {M}}\rfloor$ .
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] If x < T.children[i].max, then the value being searched for is contained in T.children[i], so the search proceeds recursively in T.children[i].
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, we search for the successor of the value *i* in T.aux.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] This gives us the index *j* of the first subtree that contains an element larger than *x*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The algorithm then returns T.children[j].min.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The element found on the children level needs to be composed with the high bits to form a complete next element.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Note that, in any case, the algorithm performs $O(1)$ work and then possibly recurses on a subtree over a universe of size $M^{1/2}$ (an $m/2$ bit universe).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] This gives a recurrence for the running time of $T(m)=T(m/2)+O(1)$ , which resolves to $O(\log m)=O(\log \log M)$ .
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, if x<T.min then we insert T.min into the subtree i responsible for T.min and then set T.min = x.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, if x>T.max then we insert x into the subtree i responsible for x and then set T.max = x.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, T.min< x < T.max so we insert x into the subtree i responsible for x.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] If T.children[i] was previously empty, then we also insert i into T.aux.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The key to the efficiency of this procedure is that inserting an element into an empty vEB tree takes *O*(1) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] So, even though the algorithm sometimes makes two recursive calls, this only occurs when the first recursive call was into an empty subtree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] This gives the same running time recurrence of ⁠ $T(m)=T(m/2)+O(1)$ ⁠ as before.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Deletion from vEB trees is the trickiest of the operations.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Otherwise, if x == T.min then we need to find the second-smallest value *y* in the vEB tree, delete it from its current location, and set T.min=y.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The second-smallest value *y* is T.children[T.aux.min].min, so it can be found in *O*(1) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] We delete *y* from the subtree that contains it.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] If x≠T.min and x≠T.max then we delete x from the subtree T.children[i] that contains *x*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] If x == T.max then we will need to find the second-largest value *y* in the vEB tree and set T.max=y.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] We start by deleting x as in previous case.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Then value *y* is either T.min or T.children[T.aux.max].max, so it can be found in *O*(1) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] In any of the above cases, if we delete the last element *x* or *y* from any subtree T.children[i] then we also delete *i* from T.aux.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Again, the efficiency of this procedure hinges on the fact that deleting from a vEB tree that contains only one element takes only constant time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] In particular, the second Delete call only executes if *x* was the only element in T.children[i] prior to the deletion.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The assumption that log *m* is an integer is unnecessary.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The operations $x{\sqrt {M}}$ and $x{\bmod {\sqrt {M}}}$ can be replaced by taking only higher-order ⌈*m*/2⌉ and the lower-order ⌊*m*/2⌋ bits of x, respectively.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] On any existing machine, this is more efficient than division or remainder computations.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] In practical implementations, especially on machines with *shift-by-k* and *find first zero* instructions, performance can further be improved by switching to a bit array once m equal to the word size (or a small multiple thereof) is reached.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Since all operations on a single word are constant time, this does not affect the asymptotic performance, but it does avoid the majority of the pointer storage and several pointer dereferences, achieving a significant practical savings in time and space with this trick.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] An optimization of vEB trees is to discard empty subtrees.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] This makes vEB trees quite compact when they contain many elements, because no subtrees are created until something needs to be added to them.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Initially, each element added creates about log(*m*) new trees containing about *m*/2 pointers all together.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] As the tree grows, more and more subtrees are reused, especially the larger ones.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The implementation described above uses pointers and occupies a total space of *O*(*M*) = *O*(2*m*), proportional to the size of the key universe.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] One can show that *S*(*M*) = *O*(*M*) by induction.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] The *O*(*M*) space usage of vEB trees is an enormous overhead unless a large fraction of the universe of keys is being stored.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] This is one reason why vEB trees are not popular in practice.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] This limitation can be addressed by changing the array used to store children to another data structure.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] One possibility is to use only a fixed number of bits per level, which results in a trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Alternatively, each array may be replaced by a hash table, reducing the space to *O*(*n* log log *M*) (where n is the number of elements stored in the data structure) at the expense of making the data structure randomized.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] x-fast tries and the more complicated y-fast tries have comparable update and query times to vEB trees and use randomized hash tables to reduce the space used. x-fast tries use *O*(*n* log *M*) space while y-fast tries use *O*(*n*) space.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Fusion trees are another type of tree data structure that implements an associative array on w-bit integers on a finite universe.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] They use word-level parallelism and bit manipulation techniques to achieve *O*(log*w* *n*) time for predecessor/successor queries and updates, where *w* is the word size.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Fusion trees use *O*(*n*) space and can be made dynamic with hashing or exponential trees.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Lenhof and Smid present a variant of the vEB tree which uses space *O*(*n*) and take *O*(1) expected amortized time for inserting an element, under the restriction that insertions are in increasing order; in other words, the inserted element is always the new maximum.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] This structure uses dynamic perfect hashing to implement the tree in small space and moreover decrease the size of the tree by a log log *M* factor by keeping at the leaves buckets of size log log *M*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] A space-efficient and partially persistent version of vEB trees was presented by Dietz and Raman.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] This version uses *O*(*n*) space, and supports an insert in the current version in *O*(log log *M*) amortized and expected time, while a query on any version remains *O*(log log *M*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] There is a verified implementation in Isabelle (proof assistant).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Both functional correctness and time bounds are proved.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/van-emde-boas-tree] Efficient imperative Standard ML code can be generated.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] In computer science, an **x-fast trie** is a data structure for storing integers from a bounded domain.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] It supports exact and predecessor or successor queries in time *O*(log log *M*), using *O*(*n* log *M*) space, where *n* is the number of stored values and *M* is the maximum value in the domain.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] The structure was proposed by Dan Willard in 1982, along with the more complicated y-fast trie, as a way to improve the space usage of van Emde Boas trees, while retaining the *O*(log log *M*) query time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] An x-fast trie is a bitwise trie: a binary tree where each subtree stores values whose binary representations start with a common prefix.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Each internal node is labeled with the common prefix of the values in its subtree and typically, the left child adds a 0 to the end of the prefix, while the right child adds a 1.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] The binary representation of an integer between 0 and *M* − 1 uses ⌈log2 *M*⌉ bits, so the height of the trie is *O*(log *M*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] All values in the x-fast trie are stored at the leaves.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Internal nodes are stored only if they have leaves in their subtree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] If an internal node would have no left child, it stores a pointer to the smallest leaf in its right subtree instead, called a *descendant* pointer.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Likewise, if it would have no right child, it stores a pointer to the largest leaf in its left subtree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Each leaf stores a pointer to its predecessor and successor, thereby forming a doubly linked list.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Finally, there is a hash table for each level that contains all the nodes on that level.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Together, these hash tables form the level-search structure (LSS).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] To guarantee the worst-case query times, these hash tables should use dynamic perfect hashing or cuckoo hashing.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] The total space usage is *O*(*n* log *M*), since each element has a root-to-leaf path of length *O*(log *M*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Like van Emde Boas trees, x-fast tries support the operations of an *ordered associative array*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Finding the value associated with a key *k* that is in the data structure can be done in constant time by looking up *k* in *LSS*[0], which is a hash table on all the leaves.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] To find the successor or predecessor of a key *k*, we first find *A**k*, the lowest ancestor of *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] This is the node in the trie that has the longest common prefix with *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] To find *A**k*, we perform a binary search on the levels.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] We start at level *h*/2, where *h* is the height of the trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] On each level, we query the corresponding hash table in the level-search structure with the prefix of *k* of the right length.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] If a node with that prefix does not exist, we know that *A**k* must be at a higher level and we restrict our search to those.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] If a node with that prefix does exist, *A**k* can not be at a higher level, so we restrict our search to the current and lower levels.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Once we find the lowest ancestor of *k*, we know that it has leaves in one of its subtrees (otherwise it wouldn't be in the trie) and *k* should be in the other subtree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Therefore, the descendant pointer points to the successor or the predecessor of *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Depending on which one we are looking for, we might have to take one step in the linked list to the next or previous leaf.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Since the trie has height *O*(log *M*), the binary search for the lowest ancestor takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] After that, the successor or predecessor can be found in constant time, so the total query time is *O*(log log *M*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] To insert a key-value pair (*k*, *v*), we first find the predecessor and successor of *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Then we create a new leaf for *k*, insert it in the linked list of leaves between the successor and predecessor, and give it a pointer to *v*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Next, we walk from the root to the new leaf, creating the necessary nodes on the way down, inserting them into the respective hash tables and updating descendant pointers where necessary.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Since we have to walk down the entire height of the trie, this process takes *O*(log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] To delete a key *k*, we find its leaf using the hash table on the leaves.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] We remove it from the linked list, but remember which were the successor and predecessor.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Then we walk from the leaf to the root of the trie, removing all nodes whose subtree only contained *k* and updating the descendant pointers where necessary.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Descendant pointers that used to point to *k* will now point to either the successor or predecessor of *k*, depending on which subtree is missing.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Like insertion, this takes *O*(log *M*) time, as we have to walk through every level of the trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] Willard introduced x-fast tries largely as an introduction to y-fast tries, which provide the same query time, while using only *O*(*n*) space and allowing insertions and deletions in *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/x-fast-trie] A compression technique similar to patricia tries can be used to significantly reduce the space usage of x-fast tries in practice.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] In computer science, a **y-fast trie** is a data structure for storing integers from a bounded domain.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] It supports exact and predecessor or successor queries in time *O*(log log *M*), using *O*(*n*) space, where *n* is the number of stored values and *M* is the maximum value in the domain.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] The structure was proposed by Dan Willard in 1983 to decrease the *O*(*n* log *M*) space used by an x-fast trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] A y-fast trie consists of two data structures: the top half is an x-fast trie and the lower half consists of a number of balanced binary trees.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] The keys are divided into groups of *O*(log *M*) consecutive elements and for each group a balanced binary search tree is created.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] To facilitate efficient insertion and deletion, each group contains at least (log *M*)/4 and at most 2 log *M* elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] For each balanced binary search tree a representative *r* is chosen.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] These representatives are stored in the x-fast trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Initially, the representative of a tree will be an integer between the minimum and maximum element in its tree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Since the x-fast trie stores *O*(*n* / log *M*) representatives and each representative occurs in *O*(log *M*) hash tables, this part of the y-fast trie uses *O*(*n*) space.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] The balanced binary search trees store *n* elements in total which uses *O*(*n*) space.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Hence, in total a y-fast trie uses *O*(*n*) space.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Like van Emde Boas trees and x-fast tries, y-fast tries support the operations of an *ordered associative array*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] A key *k* can be stored in either the tree of the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* or in the tree of the predecessor of *r* since the representative of a binary search tree need not be an element stored in its tree.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Hence, one first finds the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* in the x-fast trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Using this representative, one retrieves the predecessor of *r*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] These two representatives point to two balanced binary search trees, both of which one searches for *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Finding the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* in the x-fast trie takes *O*(log log *M*).
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Using *r*, finding its predecessor takes constant time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Searching the two balanced binary search trees containing *O*(log *M*) elements each takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Hence, a key *k* can be found, and its value retrieved, in *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Similarly to the key *k* itself, its successor can be stored in either the tree of the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* or in the tree of the predecessor of *r*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Hence, to find the successor of a key *k*, one first searches the x-fast trie for the smallest representative greater than *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Next, one uses this representative to retrieve its predecessor in the x-fast trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] These two representatives point to two balanced binary search trees, which one searches for the successor of *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Finding the smallest representative *r* greater than *k* in the x-fast trie takes *O*(log log *M*) time and using *r* to find its predecessor takes constant time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Hence, the successor of a key *k* can be found, and its value retrieved, in *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Searching for the predecessor of a key *k* is highly similar to finding its successor.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] One searches the x-fast trie for the largest representative *r* smaller than *k* and one uses *r* to retrieve its predecessor in the x-fast trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Finally, one searches the two balanced binary search trees of these two representatives for the predecessor of *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] To insert a new key/value pair (*k*, *v*), one first needs to determine in which balanced binary search tree one needs to insert *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] To this end, one finds the tree *T* containing the successor of *k*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] To ensure that all balanced binary search trees contain *O*(log *M*) elements, one splits *T* into two balanced binary trees and removes its representative from the x-fast trie if it contains more than 2 log *M* elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Each of the two new balanced binary search trees contains at most log *M* + 1 elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] One picks a representative for each tree and insert these into the x-fast trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Finding the successor of *k* takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Inserting *k* into a balanced binary search tree that contains *O*(log *M*) elements also takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Splitting a binary search tree that contains *O*(log *M*) elements can be done in *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Finally, inserting and deleting the three representatives takes *O*(log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] However, since one splits the tree at most once every *O*(log *M*) insertions and deletions, this takes constant amortized time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Therefore, inserting a new key/value pair takes *O*(log log *M*) amortized time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Deletions are very similar to insertions.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] One first finds the key *k* in one of the balanced binary search trees and delete it from this tree *T*.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] To ensure that all balanced binary search trees contain *O*(log *M*) elements, one merges *T* with the balanced binary search tree of its successor or predecessor if it contains less than (log *M*)/4 elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] The representatives of the merged trees are removed from the x-fast trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] It is possible for the merged tree to contain more than 2 log *M* elements.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] If this is the case, the newly formed tree is split into two trees of about equal size.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Next, one picks a new representative for each of the new trees and one inserts these into the x-fast trie.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Finding the key *k* takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Deleting *k* from a balanced binary search tree that contains *O*(log *M*) elements also takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Merging and possibly splitting the balanced binary search trees takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Finally, deleting the old representatives and inserting the new representatives into the x-fast trie takes *O*(log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Merging and possibly splitting the balanced binary search tree, however, is done at most once for every *O*(log *M*) insertions and deletions.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Hence, it takes constant amortized time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Therefore, deleting a key/value pair takes *O*(log log *M*) amortized time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Note that if the element we want to delete is a leaf of the X-fast trie, then we put a note saying that this number is here just to separate two binary search trees, and this number will not be returned.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] In this case, the number will not be actually removed.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] This will take *O*(1) time, and finding the key k takes *O*(log log *M*) time.
[src:van-emde-boas-tree/y-fast-trie] Therefore, the time complexity is *O*(log log *M*).
